            <fragment start="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/40/1:270)" end="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/42/1:163)" progress="0.382775">
                <text>
 I want to suggest that to write to your best abilities, it behooves you to construct your own toolbox and then build up enough muscle so you can carry it with you.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:946df3ce-9795-4e80-bfdd-92473e4210e1</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-04T21:58:36Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/240/2:746)" end="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/242:0)" progress="0.454545">
                <text>Writing is seduction. Good talk is part of seduction. If not so, why do so many couples who start the evening at dinner wind up in bed?
</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:cb4e59f1-2f6c-4a0a-9308-0fbf318d8a0a</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-03T07:59:51Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/152/1:102)" end="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/154/3:179)" progress="0.416268">
                <text>: The adverb is not your friend.
 Adverbs, you will remember from your own version of Business English, are words that modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs. They’re the ones that usually end in -ly. Adverbs, like the passive voice, seem to have been created with the timid writer in mind. With the passive voice, the writer usually expresses fear of not being taken seriously; </text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:79d64efb-5f4c-4322-aa0f-220ce09ffe6e</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-03T22:41:38Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/190/1:660)" end="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/192/1:127)" progress="0.430622">
                <text>
 I’m convinced that fear is at the root of most bad writing. If one is writing for one’s own pleasure, that fear may be mild</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:d81f5c11-f2cd-47b3-80ad-ea559550604a</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-04T21:58:25Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/240/2:453)" end="text/part0011.html#point(/1/4/240/2:654)" progress="0.454545">
                <text>The object of fiction isn’t grammatical correctness but to make the reader welcome and then tell a story  . . . . to make him/her forget, whenever possible, that he/she is reading a story at all.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:5589c572-0ce7-400a-add2-9aec1528269d</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T21:50:22Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/104/1:452)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/104/1:626)" progress="0.521531">
                <text>In both writing and sleeping, we learn to be physically still at the same time we are encouraging our minds to unlock from the humdrum rational thinking of our daytime lives.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:71568193-e213-4ad7-b55c-4987a0baa25b</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-10T21:13:11Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/368/5:442)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/368/9:119)" progress="0.660287">
                <text>You can’t please all of the readers all of the time; you can’t please even some of the readers all of the time, but you really ought to try to please at least some of the readers some of the time. I</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:9230cb17-aea1-4dd8-86ca-e657c2cc72ca</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T06:45:52Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/92/3:204)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/92/3:387)" progress="0.511962">
                <text>. The combination of a healthy body and a stable relationship with a self-reliant woman who takes zero shit from me or anyone else has made the continuity of my working life possible.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:e87e1053-8943-4f88-90f0-efdd0af0c344</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T06:38:36Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/55:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/56/3:235)" progress="0.497608">
                <text>Talent renders the whole idea of rehearsal meaningless; when you find something at which you are talented, you do it (whatever it is) until your fingers bleed or your eyes are ready to fall out of your head. Even when no one is listening (or reading, or watching), every outing is a bravura performance, because you as the creator are happy. Perhaps even ecstatic.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:a1ff3430-af5e-443b-9871-8eaf32535731</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-21T22:56:54Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/144/3:244)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/144/3:453)" progress="0.545455">
                <text>—I want you to understand that my basic belief about the making of stories is that they pretty much make themselves. The job of the writer is to give them a place to grow (and to transcribe them, of course).</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:3db91d83-156c-4131-ab03-b897b462e37f</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-24T20:27:01Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/215:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/216/1:188)" progress="0.583732">
                <text>Description begins with visualization of what it is you want the reader to experience. It ends with your translating what you see in your mind into words on the page. It’s far from easy.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:5e7571e4-0971-4a2f-a699-a67666b4c298</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-10T21:11:48Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/362/1:105)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/362/1:183)" progress="0.660287">
                <text> practice is invaluable (and should feel good, really not like practice at all</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:49045975-91dd-4b56-99ef-4e429aba17d0</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-05T05:56:56Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/20/3:300)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/20/6:309)" progress="0.478469">
                <text>There is a muse,1 but he’s not going to come fluttering down into your writing room and scatter creative fairy-dust all over your typewriter or computer station. He lives in the ground. He’s a basement guy. You have to descend to his level, and once you get down there you have to furnish an apartment for him to live in. </text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:32f907f1-b587-4ee6-83fe-ae95a4b83647</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-12T20:55:38Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/141:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/143:0)" progress="0.54067">
                <text>In my view, stories and novels consist of three parts: narration, which moves the story from point A to point B and finally to point Z; description, which creates a sensory reality for the reader; and dialogue, which brings characters to life through their speech.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:1089e075-e448-4cbb-a917-f7726ec12db9</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T06:39:24Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/57:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/58/1:340)" progress="0.497608">
                <text>The real importance of reading is that it creates an ease and intimacy with the process of writing; one comes to the country of the writer with one’s papers and identification pretty much in order. Constant reading will pull you into a place (a mind-set, if you like the phrase) where you can write eagerly and without self-consciousness.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:4e179afd-c773-4354-9d28-09ea1e4ed1e7</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T21:59:11Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/123:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/124/1:486)" progress="0.5311">
                <text>Book-buyers aren’t attracted, by and large, by the literary merits of a novel; book-buyers want a good story to take with them on the airplane, something that will first fascinate them, then pull them in and keep them turning the pages. This happens, I think, when readers recognize the people in a book, their behaviors, their surroundings, and their talk. When the reader hears strong echoes of his or her own life and beliefs, he or she is apt to become more invested in the story.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:c3a0701c-bbac-4e46-881a-5d267cb49bcb</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-21T22:56:21Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/143:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/144/1:86)" progress="0.545455">
                <text>You may wonder where plot is in all this. The answer—my answer, anyway—is nowhere.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:4ded734c-eed5-40e8-8eaf-d5818655c160</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T21:52:22Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/104/1:899)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/106/1:232)" progress="0.521531">
                <text>
 But you need the room, you need the door, and you need the determination to shut the door. You need a concrete goal, as well. The longer you keep to these basics, the easier the act of writing will become. Don’t wait for the muse.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:9166c7f9-9b32-48b4-9b07-2bebb3d1552d</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-24T20:42:31Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/255:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/256/1:161)" progress="0.602871">
                <text>As with all other aspects of the narrative art, you will improve with practice, but practice will never make you perfect. Why should it? What fun would that be? </text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:721230cb-7bb8-411d-af21-da0ba0e37ed3</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-24T20:41:59Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/262/3:106)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/262/3:192)" progress="0.607656">
                <text>one of the cardinal rules of good fiction is never tell us a thing if you can show us,</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:af0f7be0-cfe0-40bd-a4ca-5b21f3c9b747</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-12T20:53:21Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/127:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/128/1:234)" progress="0.535885">
                <text>Write what you like, then imbue it with life and make it unique by blending in your own personal knowledge of life, friendship, relationships, sex, and work. Especially work. People love to read about work. God knows why, but they do.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:f42681ed-85d1-4a62-b376-1d767ff92220</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T06:48:27Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/102/1:730)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/104:0)" progress="0.521531">
                <text>When you write, you want to get rid of the world, do you not? Of course you do. When you’re writing, you’re creating your own worlds.
</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:32ffefc9-0669-492c-8c30-99595f22a54f</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T21:49:57Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/104/1:55)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/104/1:141)" progress="0.521531">
                <text>Like your bedroom, your writing room should be private, a place where you go to dream.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:aab8e103-1540-4f02-b265-5f794c3f95e2</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-10T21:50:11Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/104/1:142)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/104/1:451)" progress="0.521531">
                <text>Your schedule—in at about the same time every day, out when your thousand words are on paper or disk—exists in order to habituate yourself, to make yourself ready to dream just as you make yourself ready to sleep by going to bed at roughly the same time each night and following the same ritual as you go.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:15cba414-3d45-4671-bf78-53b5741fcc6e</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-21T22:56:32Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/144/1:256)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/144/3:193)" progress="0.545455">
                <text>I distrust plot for two reasons: first, because our lives are largely plotless, even when you add in all our reasonable precautions and careful planning; and second, because I believe plotting and the spontaneity of real creation aren’t compatible.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:3fba7154-f9e9-4f28-a30b-68521d218e14</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-09-05T05:57:17Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/25:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/26/1:96)" progress="0.478469">
                <text>If you want to be a writer, you must do two things above all others: read a lot and write a lot.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:403403f5-1970-4207-8106-a5ef896bffa2</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-12T15:50:56Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/436/1:63)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/436/1:263)" progress="0.703349">
                <text>starting with the questions and thematic concerns is a recipe for bad fiction. Good fiction always begins with story and progresses to theme; it almost never begins with theme and progresses to story.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:868bae6a-2a7e-4cfb-bb25-3cde0c5846ea</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-12T15:53:09Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/447:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/448/1:107)" progress="0.708134">
                <text>This first draft—the All-Story Draft—should be written with no help (or interference) from anyone else.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:a73a9367-13e1-45ee-a547-1ecd01b1e9a6</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-12T15:53:49Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/448/1:575)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/450:0)" progress="0.712919">
                <text>Let your hope of success (and your fear of failure) carry you on, difficult as that can be. There’ll be time to show off what you’ve done when you finish  . . . . but even after finishing I think you must be cautious and give yourself a chance to think while the story is still like a field of freshly fallen snow, absent of any tracks save your own.
</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:4c5fe5b7-5e64-4ed0-aa5a-14c5afe92bf3</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-12T15:57:51Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/468/1:357)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/470/3:93)" progress="0.722488">
                <text>This is the way it should be, the reason you waited. It’s always easier to kill someone else’s darlings than it is to kill your own.
 With six weeks’ worth of recuperation time, you’ll also be able to see any glaring holes in the plot or character development. I’m talking about holes big enough to drive a truck through. It’s amazing how some of these things can elude the writer while he or she is occupied with the daily work of composition. And listen—if you spot a few of these big holes, you are forbidden to feel depressed about them or to beat up on yourself. Screw-ups happen to the best of us. </text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:be9ec27d-215c-45fb-b953-50230f31aeda</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-12T16:01:17Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/478/1:349)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/478/3:150)" progress="0.727273">
                <text>What I want most of all is resonance, something that will linger for a little while in Constant Reader’s mind (and heart) after he or she has closed the book and put it up on the shelf.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:4f5e5436-dbf0-4784-8403-a02eefdac0da</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-17T21:30:52Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/601:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/602/3:41)" progress="0.794258">
                <text>In truth, I’ve found that any day’s routine interruptions and distractions don’t much hurt a work in progress and may actually help it in some ways. It is, after all, the dab of grit that seeps into an oyster’s shell that makes the pearl, not pearl-making seminars with other oysters.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:c27a7497-df1e-49bf-a479-65c77af18a66</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-17T21:36:27Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/618/1:598)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/619:0)" progress="0.803828">
                <text>Do you need someone to make you a paper badge with the word WRITER on it before you can believe you are one? God, I hope not.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:fe9082f2-afa2-45e6-8781-af3f50d43fc0</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-10-17T21:36:45Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/617:1)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/618/1:396)" progress="0.803828">
                <text>Writing courses and seminars do offer at least one undeniable benefit: in them, the desire to write fiction or poetry is taken seriously. For aspiring writers who have been looked upon with pitying condescension by their friends and relatives (“You better not quit your day job just yet!” is a popular line, usually delivered with a hideous Bob’s-yer-uncle grin), this is a wonderful thing.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:04ca8647-a904-4c34-a6c7-ecadfbce4b5b</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-11-01T23:23:43Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/728/1:327)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/730/1:183)" progress="0.851675">
                <text>same: Do you do it for the money, honey?
 The answer is no. Don’t now and never did. Yes, I’ve made a great deal of dough from my fiction, but I never set a single word down on paper with the thought of being paid for it.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:af1bb7af-8448-4223-8bab-830916335d26</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-11-01T23:24:05Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/730/1:492)" end="text/part0012.html#point(/1/4/732:0)" progress="0.851675">
                <text>—I did it for the buzz. I did it for the pure joy of the thing. And if you can do it for joy, you can do it forever.
</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:6dcb9742-8d3c-4e4d-ac03-3cc8b2ce5e45</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-11-02T23:59:16Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0013.html#point(/1/4/112/1:179)" end="text/part0013.html#point(/1/4/114:0)" progress="0.904306">
                <text>it seems to me that one of the things marriage is about is casting the tiebreaking vote when you just can’t decide what you should do next.
</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:62b7d0d0-3c6c-407d-8b11-d8926468020a</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-11-03T00:03:05Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0013.html#point(/1/4/138/5:1)" end="text/part0013.html#point(:1)" progress="0.913876">
                <text>Writing is magic, as much the water of life as any other creative art. The water is free. So drink.
 Drink and be filled up.
</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
    <annotation>
        <dc:identifier>urn:uuid:82027062-d73e-4c41-ab1d-e1c0beb3a541</dc:identifier>
        <dc:date>2024-11-03T00:03:22Z</dc:date>
        <dc:creator>urn:uuid:acbea043-dcae-4a2f-9505-2dfd12705ad5</dc:creator>
        <target>
            <fragment start="text/part0013.html#point(/1/4/138/3:203)" end="text/part0013.html#point(/1/4/138/5:0)" progress="0.913876">
                <text>: you can, you should, and if you’re brave enough to start, you will.</text>
            </fragment>
        </target>
    </annotation>
</annotationSet>